## 2) Multi-intent detection (how you stop missing “combine both” answers)

Many queries are *two questions in one*. You want to detect that and force multi-source retrieval.

### A. Cheap heuristics that work well

Mark `multi_intent=true` if any of these:

* Query contains conjunction patterns: **“and”, “also”, “plus”, “as well as”**
* Multiple question marks or multiple interrogatives (“why … and what …”)
* Two distinct keyword families appear (e.g., “pipeline” + “policy”, “decided” + “implementation”)
* A “decision + implementation” combo:

  * “what did we decide” (Jam) + “where is it” (GitLab)
* A “incident + process” combo:

  * “why did it fail” (GitLab) + “what’s the rollback process” (SharePoint)

### B. Intent decomposition (optional but strong)

Split the query into sub-questions:

* Q1: “Why is CI failing?” → GitLab
* Q2: “What’s the official rollback process?” → SharePoint

Then route each sub-question separately and merge.

This can be rule-based initially; later you can let an LLM do decomposition when the heuristics trigger.

